---
description: Enforces strict separation of concerns — no inline CSS, JS, or template strings in Python, tests, or HTML
alwaysApply: true
---

# Strict Separation of Concerns

MuseHub uses a three-layer architecture. Each layer must stay in its own file type. Crossing boundaries is always an anti-pattern.

| What | Where | Never in |
|------|-------|----------|
| Markup (structure) | Jinja2 `.html` templates | Python, TypeScript |
| Styles | SCSS `_*.scss` partials → compiled `app.css` | `style=""` attributes, `<style>` tags, Python strings |
| Behaviour | TypeScript `static/js/**/*.ts` → compiled `app.js` | `<script>` tags in templates, `onchange=` / `onclick=` attributes, Python strings |

## ❌ Anti-patterns — never do these

```python
# Inline CSS in Python
ctx["style"] = "color: red; font-size: 14px"

# HTML/template strings in Python
return HTMLResponse("<div class='card'>...</div>")

# Script strings in Python
ctx["init_js"] = "const cfg = " + json.dumps(data)
```

```html
<!-- Inline styles in Jinja2 -->
<div style="color:red;margin:8px">...</div>

<!-- Inline event handlers in Jinja2 -->
<button onclick="doThing()">click</button>
<select onchange="this.form.submit()">

<!-- <script> blocks with business logic in templates -->
<script>
  const data = {{ items | tojson }};
  fetch('/api/...').then(r => r.json()).then(renderChart);
</script>
```

```python
# Tests asserting CSS class names or JS variable names
assert "tab-btn" in response.text          # ❌ fragile — class name can change
assert "let sessions" in response.text     # ❌ JS moved to .ts module
assert "pr.mergedAt" in response.text      # ❌ JS implementation detail
assert "badge-merged" in response.text     # ❌ CSS class, not semantic content
```

## ✅ Correct patterns

```html
<!-- Styles: use SCSS class names only -->
<div class="cr-stat-card">...</div>

<!-- Behaviour: attach in TypeScript via addEventListener -->
<!-- In template: -->
<select id="sort-select" name="sort">...</select>
<!-- In .ts module: -->
document.getElementById('sort-select')?.addEventListener('change', handler);

<!-- Data from server → client: use a typed JSON block, never inline script -->
<script id="page-data" type="application/json">{{ page_json | tojson }}</script>
```

```python
# Tests: assert status codes and semantic text content, not CSS or JS strings
assert response.status_code == 200
assert "gabriel" in response.text          # ✅ actual user data
assert "No pull requests" in response.text # ✅ visible UI text
# For behaviour, test the JSON API endpoints instead:
resp = await client.get("/api/v1/repos/{id}/credits")
assert resp.json()["totalContributors"] == 3
```

## Allowed exceptions

- `style=""` **only** for dynamic values that cannot be expressed as SCSS (e.g. `width: {{ pct }}%` for data-driven bars, `background: hsl({{ hue }}, ...)` for deterministic avatar colours). Keep it to a single property; never use it for layout or typography.
- `onchange="this.form.submit()"` on a plain `<select>` inside a `<form method="get">` is acceptable as a progressive-enhancement pattern (no JS dependency).
